# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tap-and-die
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] In machining, **2.5D** refers to a surface which is a projection of a plane into 3rd dimension – although the object is 3-dimensional, there are no overhanging elements possible.
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] Objects of this type are often represented as a contour map that gives the height (*i.e.*, thickness or depth) of the object at each point.
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] 2.5D objects can be machined on a 3-axis milling machine, and do not require any of the features of a higher-axis machine to produce.
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] A typical example involves an XY table that positions for each hole center, where the spindle (Z-axis) then completes a fixed cycle for drilling by plunging and retracting axially.
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] The code for a 2.5D machining is significantly less than 3D contour machining, and the software and hardware requirements are (traditionally) less expensive.
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] **Drilling and tapping centers** are inexpensive, limited-duty machining centers that began as a 2.5-axis market category, although many late-model ones are 3-axis because the software and hardware costs have dropped with advancing technology.
[src:tap-and-die/2-5d-machining] A 2.5D image is a simplified three-dimensional (x, y, z) surface representation that contains at most one depth (z) value for every point in the (x, y) plane.
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] The product changed ownership many times throughout the 20th century and was bought by its current owners, the WD-40 Company, in 1995.
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] The current marketing slogan is "The Tool Kit In A Can," with the logo of the text "3 in" inside a large numeral "1".
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] A few other products are now produced under the 3-in-1 brand, including a white lithium grease, silicone spray, and oil with added PTFE.
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] In 2000, the can was redesigned to look like the early 20th century oil can design, with a hemisphere base and tapered straight spout.
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] An advertisement in *The Church Standard* magazine (April 13, 1901, p 867) offers 3 in 1 Oil as a perfect polish for pianos.
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] It claimed that the oil was "long lasting" and did not come off on the clothes.
[src:tap-and-die/3-in-one-oil] An advertisement in *Good Housekeeping* (March 1930) suggests using 3 in 1 Oil as a furniture polish, by wringing out a water-soaked cloth and putting 3 in 1 Oil on it, wiping the dirt off the surface with the oiled cloth, then polishing the surface clean with a dry soft cloth.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining works by forcing the abrasive particles, or grains, into the surface of the workpiece so that each particle cuts away a small bit of material.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining is similar to conventional machining, such as milling or turning, because each of the abrasive particles acts like a miniature cutting tool.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] However, unlike conventional machining the grains are much smaller than a cutting tool, and the geometry and orientation of individual grains are not well defined.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] As a result, abrasive machining is less power efficient and generates more heat.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] The grain size may be different based on the machining.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] For rough grinding, coarse abrasives are used.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] For fine grinding, fine grains (abrasives) are used.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining processes can be divided into two categories based on how the grains are applied to the workpiece.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] In bonded abrasive processes, the particles are held together within a matrix, and their combined shape determines the geometry of the finished workpiece.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] For example, in grinding the particles are bonded together in a wheel.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] As the grinding wheel is fed into the part, its shape is transferred onto the workpiece.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] In loose abrasive processes, there is no structure connecting the grains.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] They may be applied without lubrication as dry powder, or they may be mixed with a lubricant to form a slurry.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Since the grains can move independently, they must be forced into the workpiece with another object like a polishing cloth or a lapping plate.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Common abrasive processes are listed below.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] The most important property of an abrasive is its hardness.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] For abrasive grains to effectively cut, they must be significantly harder than the workpiece material.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] They can be grouped based on their hardness into two categories: conventional abrasives and superabrasives.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasive materials have been used since the advent of machining.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] They are made of materials that exist naturally on Earth, and they are abundant and cheap.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasives can suitably machine most materials.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Superabrasives are much harder than conventional abrasives.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive-machining] Since they are much more expensive, they are used when conventional abrasives will not suffice.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:tap-and-die/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloy steels divide into two groups: low and high alloy.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The boundary between the two is disputed.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] William Smith and Javad Hashemi define the difference at 4.0%, while Paul Degarmo, *et al.*, define it at 8.0%.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The simplest steels are iron (Fe) alloyed with (0.1% to 1%) carbon (C) and nothing else (excepting slight impurities); these are called carbon steels.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] However, alloy steel encompasses steels with additional (metal) alloying elements.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Common alloyants include manganese (Mn) (the most common), nickel (Ni), chromium (Cr), molybdenum (Mo), vanadium (V), silicon (Si), and boron (B).
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Less common alloyants include Aluminium (Al), cobalt (Co), copper (Cu), cerium (Ce), niobium (Nb), titanium (Ti), tungsten (W), tin (Sn), zinc (Zn), lead (Pb), and zirconium (Zr).
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloy steels variously improve strength, hardness, toughness, wear resistance, corrosion resistance, hardenability, and hot hardness.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] To achieve these improved properties the metal may require specific heat treating, combined with strict cooling protocols.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Although alloy steels have been made for centuries, their metallurgy was not well understood until the advancing chemical science of the nineteenth century revealed their compositions.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloy steels from earlier times were expensive luxuries made on the model of "secret recipes" and forged into tools such as knives and swords.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Machine age alloy steels were tool steels and stainless steels.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Because of iron's ferromagnetic properties, some alloys find important applications where their responses to magnetism are valued, including in electric motors and in transformers.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloying elements enable specific properties.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] As a guideline, alloying elements are added in lower percentages (less than 5%) to increase strength or hardenability, or in larger percentages (over 5%) to improve corrosion resistance or temperature stability.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The alloying elements tend to form either solid solutions, compounds or carbides.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloying elements can have an effect on the eutectoid temperature.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The properties of steel depend on its microstructure: the arrangement of different phases, some harder, some with greater ductility.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] At the atomic level, the four phases of auto steel include martensite (the hardest yet most brittle), bainite (less hard), ferrite (more ductile), and austenite (the most ductile).
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The phases are arranged by steelmakers by manipulating intervals (sometimes by seconds only) and temperatures of the heating and cooling process.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloy steel pipes are widely used for transporting crude oil, natural gas, and petroleum products.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Their high strength and corrosion resistance make them ideal for high-pressure and high-temperature environments.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Other pipes are used in boilers, heat exchangers in thermal and nuclear power plants.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] They can withstand extreme temperatures and pressure conditions efficiently.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloy steel pipes are also used for safely handling corrosive chemicals and high-temperature fluids.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Their durability ensures long service life in harsh processing environments.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] They are furthermore used in structural applications such as bridges, buildings, and industrial frameworks.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Their strength and load-bearing capacity provide long-term reliability.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Alloy steel pipes are also used in manufacturing vehicle components and heavy machinery parts.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Their toughness and wear resistance support demanding mechanical operations.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The wide applications of alloy steel pipes across industries highlight their strength, durability, and reliability in demanding environments.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] From energy and infrastructure to manufacturing, the applications of alloy steel continue to support critical industrial operations.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] TRIP steels transform from relatively ductile to relatively hard under deformation such as in a car crash.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Deformation transforms austenitic microstructure to martensitic microstructure.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] TRIP steels use relatively high carbon content to create the austenitic microstructure.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Relatively high silicon/aluminum content suppresses carbide precipitation in the bainite region and helps accelerate ferrite/bainite formation.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] This helps retain carbon to support austenite at room temperature.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] A specific cooling process reduces the austenite/martensite transformation during forming.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] TRIP steels typically require an isothermal hold at an intermediate temperature during cooling, which produces some bainite.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The additional silicon/carbon requires weld cycle modification, such as the use of pulsating welding or dilution welding.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] In one approach steel is heated to a high temperature, cooled somewhat, held stable for an interval and then quenched.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] This produces islands of austenite surrounded by a matrix of softer ferrite, with regions of harder bainite and martensite.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The resulting product can absorb energy without fracturing, making it useful for auto parts such as bumpers and pillars.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Three generations of advanced, high-strength steel are available.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The first was created in the 1990s, increasing strength and ductility.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] A second generation used new alloys to further increase ductility, but were expensive and difficult to manufacture.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Refined heating and cooling patterns increase strength at some cost in ductility (vs 2nd generation).
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] These steels are claimed to approach nearly ten times the strength of earlier steels; and are much cheaper to manufacture.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] Researches created an alloy with the strength of steel and the lightness of titanium alloy.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] It combined iron, aluminum, carbon, manganese, and nickel.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The other ingredient was uniformly distributed nanometer-sized B2 intermetallic (two metals with equal numbers of atoms) particles.
[src:tap-and-die/alloy-steel] The use of nickel avoided problems with earlier attempts to use B2, while increasing ductility.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:tap-and-die/aluminium-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] (left), and die in a wrench for creating male threads (right).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] In the context of threading, **taps** and **dies** are two classes of tools used to create or repair screw threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A tap is used to cut or form the female portion of the mating pair (e.g. a nut).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A die is a cutting tool used to cut the male portion of the mating pair (e.g. a bolt).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The process of cutting or forming threads using a tap is called *tapping*, whereas the process using a die is called *threading*.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Both tools can also be used to clean up or repair a thread, which is called *chasing*.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] However using an ordinary tap or die to clean threads generally removes some material, which results in looser, weaker threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Because of this, machinists generally clean threads with special taps and dies—called *chasers*—made for that purpose.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Chasers are made of softer materials and don't cut new threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] However they still fit tighter than actual fasteners, and are fluted like regular taps and dies so debris can escape.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Car mechanics, for example, use chasers on spark plug threads, to remove corrosion and carbon build-up.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Taps and dies are available in many hardware stores, home improvement centers and automotive part retailers in common sizes and pipe (Home improvement) sizes.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Online industrial suppliers also offer taps and dies.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Manufacturers and DIY websites have instructions on how to use the tools.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] As the loads grew even heavier, bigger and stronger bolts were needed to resist breakage.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Some nuts and bolts were measured by the foot or yard.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This development eventually led to a complete replacement of wood parts with metal parts of an identical measure.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] When a wooden part broke, it usually snapped, ripped, or tore.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] With the splinters having been sanded off, the remaining parts were reassembled, encased in a makeshift mold of clay, and molten metal poured into the mold, so that an identical replacement could be made on the spot.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Metalworking taps and dies were often made by their users during the 16th and 17th centuries (especially if the user was skilled in tool making), using such tools as lathes and files for the shaping, and the smithy for hardening and tempering.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Thus builders of, for example, locomotives, firearms, or textile machinery were likely to make their own taps and dies.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] During the 19th century the machining industries evolved greatly, and the practice of buying taps and dies from suppliers specializing in them gradually supplanted most such in-house work.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Joseph Clement was one such early vendor of taps and dies, starting in 1828.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] With the introduction of more advanced milling practice in the 1860s and 1870s, tasks such as cutting a tap's flutes with a hand file became a thing of the past.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] In the early 20th century, thread-grinding practice went through significant evolution, further advancing the state of the art (and applied science) of cutting screw threads, including those of taps and dies.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] During the 19th and 20th centuries, thread standardization was evolving simultaneously with the techniques of thread generation, including taps and dies.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The largest tap and die company to exist in the United States was Greenfield Tap & Die (GTD) of Greenfield, Massachusetts.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] GTD was so vital to the Allied war effort from 1940–1945 that anti-aircraft guns were placed around its campus in anticipation of possible Axis air attack.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The GTD brand is now a part of Widia Products Group.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A *tap* cuts or forms a thread on the inside surface of a hole, creating a female surface that functions like a nut.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The tap illustrated in the top of the image has a continuous cutting edge with almost no taper — between 1 and 1.5 threads of taper is typical.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A bottoming tap is usually used to cut threads in a hole that has already been partially threaded using one of the more tapered types of tap; the tapered end ("tap chamfer") of a bottoming tap is too short to successfully start into an unthreaded hole.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] In the US, they are commonly known as bottoming taps, but in Australia and Britain they are also known as plug taps.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The tap illustrated in the middle of the image has tapered cutting edges, which assist in aligning and starting the tap into an untapped hole.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The number of tapered threads typically ranges from 3 to 5.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Plug taps are the most commonly used type of tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] In the US, they are commonly known as plug taps, whereas in Australia and Britain they are commonly known as second taps.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The small tap illustrated at the bottom of the image is similar to an intermediate tap but has a more pronounced taper to the cutting edges.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This feature gives the taper tap a very gradual cutting action that is less aggressive than that of the plug tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The number of tapered threads typically ranges from 8 to 10.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A taper tap is most often used when the material is difficult to work (e.g., alloy steel) or the tap is of a very small diameter and thus prone to breakage.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The above taps are generally referred to as hand taps, since they are manually operated.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The most common type of power driven tap is the "spiral point" plug tap, also referred to as a "gun" tap, whose cutting edges are angularly displaced relative to the tap centerline.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This feature causes the tap to continuously break the chip and eject it forward into the hole, preventing crowding.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Spiral point taps are usually used in holes that go all the way through the material, so that the chips can escape.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Spiral flute taps are widely used in high speed, automatic tapping operations due to their ability to work well in blind holes.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A forming tap, aka fluteless tap, cold forming or roll tap, functions quite differently than a cut tap, in that it forcefully displaces the metal into a thread shape upon being turned into the hole, instead of cutting metal from the sides of the hole as cutting taps do.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A forming tap has lobes periodically spaced around the tap which actually do the thread forming as the tap is advanced into a properly sized hole, and the threads behind the lobes are slightly recessed to reduce contact friction.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Since there is no need to provide space for evacuating chips, these recesses are much more subtle than a cutting tap's flutes and the tap appears very nearly just like a plain thread.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Since the tap does not produce chips, there is no need to periodically back out the tap to clear away chips, which can jam and break a cutting tap if allowed to accumulate.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The problem of accumulated chips is particularly acute in blind holes, so thread forming is particularly suited to such applications.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Forming taps only work in malleable materials such as mild steel or aluminum.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Formed threads are typically stronger than cut threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Note that the tap drill size is larger than that used for a cutting tap as shown in most tap drill tables, and an accurate hole size is required; a slightly undersized hole can break the tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Proper lubrication is essential because of the frictional forces involved, therefore a lubricating oil is used instead of cutting oil.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Form taps are much stronger than cut taps, as can be seen by cross sections of the same size tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This significantly lessens tap breakage (Tap breakage discussed below under Machine Tapping).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Form Taps last 3 to twenty times longer than cut taps.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Whether manual or automatic, the processing of tapping begins with forming (usually by drilling) and slightly countersinking a hole to a diameter somewhat smaller than the tap's major diameter.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The correct cut tap hole diameter is listed on a drill and tap size chart, a standard reference in many machine shops.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The proper diameter for the drill is called the **tap drill** size.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] where $TD$ is the tap drill size, $MD$ is the major diameter of the tap (e.g., 3⁄8 in for a 3⁄8-16 tap), and $1/N$ is the thread pitch (1⁄16 inch in the case of a 3⁄8-16 tap).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] For a 3⁄8-16 tap, the above formula would produce 5⁄16, which is the correct tap drill diameter.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The above formula ultimately results in an approximate 75% thread.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] where $TD$ is the tap drill size, $MD$ is the major diameter of the tap (e.g., 10 mm for a M10×1.5 tap), and pitch is the pitch of the thread (1.5 mm in the case of a standard M10 tap) and so the correct drill size is 8.5 mm.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This works for both fine and coarse pitches, and also produces an approximate 75% thread.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] With soft or average hardness materials, such as plastic, aluminum or mild steel, common practice is to use an intermediate (plug) tap to cut the threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] If the threads must extend to the bottom of a blind hole, the machinist uses an intermediate (plug) tap to cut threads until the point of the tap reaches bottom, and then switches to a bottoming tap to finish.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The machinist must frequently eject chips to avoid jamming or breaking the tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] With hard materials, the machinist may start with a taper tap, whose less severe diameter transition reduces the torque required to cut threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] To thread to the bottom of a blind hole, the machinist follows the taper tap with an intermediate (plug) tap, and then a bottoming tap to finish.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Tapping may either be achieved by a hand tapping by using a set of taps (first tap, second tap & final (finish) tap) or using a machine to do the tapping, such as a lathe, radial drilling machine, bench type drill machine, pillar type drill machine, vertical milling machines, HMCs, VMCs.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Machine tapping is faster, and generally more accurate because human error is eliminated.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Final tapping is achieved with single tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Although in general machine tapping is more accurate, tapping operations have traditionally been very tricky to execute due to frequent tap breakage and inconsistent quality of tapping.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] To overcome these problems, special tool holders are required to minimize the chances of tap breakage during tapping.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] These are usually classified as conventional tool holders and CNC tool holders.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Tap breakage is common, removal is difficult.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Various methods are used to remove broken taps, to include: Manually smashing the tap, Using a tap extractor, Milling, Grinding with an Omegadrill, TIG welding, and Electrical discharge machining (EDM).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The biggest problem with simple hand-tapping is accurately aligning the tap with the hole so that they are coaxial—in other words, going in straight instead of on an angle.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The operator must get this alignment close to ideal to produce good threads and not break the tap.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The deeper the thread depth, the more pronounced the effect of the angular error.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] With a depth of 1 or 2 diameters, it matters little.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] With depths beyond 2 diameters, the error becomes too pronounced to ignore.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Another fact about alignment is that the first thread cut or two establishes the direction that the rest of the threads will follow.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] You can't correct the angle after the first thread or two.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Double-lead taps and insert taps need different speeds and feeds, and different starting hole diameters than other taps.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A comprehensive reference for US tap and drill bit sizes can be found in the chart provided by Albany County Fasteners.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This chart includes detailed specifications for machine screw size, threads per inch, major and minor diameters, and appropriate drill sizes for different materials.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A *die* cuts an external thread on cylindrical material, such as a rod, which creates a male threaded piece that functions like a bolt.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Dies are generally made in two styles: solid and adjustable.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] An adjustable die may be adjusted either by an integrated screw or by a set of screws set in to the die holder (termed a "die stock").
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Integral adjusting screws may be arranged to work axially, where the movement of the adjusting screw into a threaded hole in the die forces the slit section of the die open, or tangentially where a screw threaded in to one side of the slit bears against the opposite side of the slit.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Dies without integrated screws are adjusted inside the die stock by radially arranged screws.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Two screws in the stock bear in to indentations on either side of the slit, tending to squeeze the slit closed, whilst a third screw with a tapered tip screws in to the slit forcing it open.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Working these three screws against each other adjusts the die.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Integrated screws appear to be common in the US but are almost unknown in the UK and Europe.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Solid dies cut a nominal thread form and depth, whose accuracy is subject to the precision the die was made with, and the effects of wear.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Adjustable dies can be slightly compressed or expanded to provide some compensation for wear, or to achieve different classes of thread fit (class A, B and more rarely, C).
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Adjustable taps also exist but are not common.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] These have a tip that is split through the flutes and an axial screw which forces the cutting edges slightly apart.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The work piece (blank) to be threaded, which is usually slightly smaller in diameter than the die's major diameter, is given a slight taper (chamfer) at the end that is to be threaded.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] This chamfer helps center the die on the blank and reduces the force required to start the thread cutting.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Once the die has started, it self-feeds.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Periodic reversal of the die is often required to break the chip and prevent crowding.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] used for a standard nut of that size may be used to turn them.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Rethreading dies cannot be used to cut new threads as they lack chip forming teeth.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Note, however the external profile of a die does not strictly map to its function.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Manufacturers of dies have produced models in a hex form which are intended for the creation of new threads.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] These appear identical to solid dies in all aspects besides the external shape.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Hexagonal thread cutting dies are used with a die stock with hexagonal holding features.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] The use of a suitable lubricant is essential with most tapping and threading operations.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] A low velocity air blast should be used to clear chips.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Kerosene or mineral spirits mixed with a small amount (15–25 percent) of petroleum-based cutting oil.
[src:tap-and-die/tap-and-die] Kerosene or mineral spirits mixed with a small amount (10–15 percent) of petroleum-based cutting oil.
